    <fr:p>Claim (ii) will be proven in [hodge-theory-iii-8.3.10 <fr:strong>(?)</fr:strong>].
      Claim (i) follows from (iii) of <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-iii-8.1.20"
href="hodge-theory-iii-8.1.20.xml"
taxon="Proposition"
number="8.1.20" />.
      For proper <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>, we can find a diagram as in <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-iii-8.2.1.1"
href="hodge-theory-iii-8.2.1.1.xml"
taxon="Equation"
number="8.2.1.1" /> in which <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[Y_\bullet =\bar {Y}_\bullet ]]></fr:tex>, and (iii) then follows from (iv) of <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-iii-8.1.20"
href="hodge-theory-iii-8.1.20.xml"
taxon="Proposition"
number="8.1.20" />.
      For smooth <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>, (iv) follows from <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-iii-8.2.3"
href="hodge-theory-iii-8.2.3.xml"
number="8.2.3" /> and <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-ii-3.2.15"
href="hodge-theory-ii-3.2.15.xml"
taxon="Corollary"
number="3.2.15" />.
      The general case then follows: if <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p\colon \widetilde {X}\to  X]]></fr:tex> is a resolution of singularities of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p^*\colon \operatorname {H}^\bullet (X,\mathbb {Q})\to \operatorname {H}^\bullet (\widetilde {X},\mathbb {Q})]]></fr:tex> is injective, since the Poincar√© dual transpose <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p_!]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p^*\colon \operatorname {H}^\bullet _\mathrm {c}(X,\mathbb {Q})\to \operatorname {H}^\bullet _\mathrm {c}(\widetilde {X},\mathbb {Q})]]></fr:tex> is a retraction for it.</fr:p>
  </fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
  
